 Certainly! Based on the provided ontology and image description, I will generate a Knowledge Graph in Turtle format for you. Please note that since the images are not provided, I am assuming that the environment includes components such as appliances, furniture, and objects, with their respective affordances and locations within or overlapping with other components. Here's the generated KG:

```turtle
@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .
@prefix geo: <http://www.opengis.net/ont/> .

<http://example.com/Environment> a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:comment "An environment is an area or context in which components are found."@en .

<http://example.com/Component> a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:comment "A component is a part of an environment that can be used to perform tasks or actions."@en .

<http://example.com/Appliance> a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Appliance"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "An appliance is a type of component."@en .

<http://example.com/Furniture> a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Furniture"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "A furniture is a type of component."@en .

<http://example.com/Object> a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Object"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "An object is a type of component."@en .

[http://example.com/Location, http://example.com/Location_1] a geo:FeatureOfInterest ;
    rdfs:label "Location"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "A location is a specific component within the environment"@en .

<http://example.com/Environment> owl:subClassOf owl:Class ;
    rdfs:comment "An environment has one or more components."@en .

<http://example.com/Component> owl:subClassOf owl:Class ;
    rdfs:comment "A component has one or more affordances that indicate how it can be used."@en .

[http://example.com/Location_1, http://example.com/Location_2] a geo:FeatureOfInterest ;
    rdfs:label "Location"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "A location has a name."@en .

<http://example.com/Appliance> owl:intersectionOf [ <http://example.com/Component>, <http://example.com/Furniture> ] ;
    rdfs:comment "An appliance is a component that is also furniture."@en .

<http://example.com/Furniture> owl:unionOf [ <http://example.com/Appliance>, <http://example.com/Object> ] ;
    rdfs:comment "A piece of furniture is either an appliance or an object."@en .

<http://example.com/Object> owl:unionOf [ <http://example.com/Furniture>, <http://example.com/Appliance> ] ;
    rdfs:comment "An object is a component that is also furniture and appliance."@en .

[http://example.com/Location_1, http://example.com/Location_2] geo:hasGeometry [ <http://example.com/Point> ] ;
    rdfs:label "Location"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "The location has a point."@en .

[http://example.com/Location, http://example.com/Location_1] geo:hasGeometry [ <http://example.com/Point> ] ;
    rdfs:label "Location"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "The location has a point."@en .

[http://example.com/Location_2, http://example.com/Location] geo:hasGeometry [ <http://example.com/Point> ] ;
    rdfs:label "Location"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "The location has a point."@en .
```

This Knowledge Graph describes an environment with components (appliances, furniture, objects) and their locations. The affordances are not explicitly shown in the image descriptions provided, so I am unable to include them in this output. Please provide more details or specific affordances if you need them included in the KG.
